FOOT AND MOUTH DISEASE - SOUTH KOREA: (NORTH GYEONGSANG) BOVINE, SUSPECTED, REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
***************************************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Tue 4 Dec 2012
Source: The Korea Times [edited]
http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2012/12/116_126148.html


A suspected case of foot-and-mouth disease (FMD) has been reported on a small cattle farm in Cheongdo, North Gyeongsang Province, government and industry officials said Tuesday [4 Dec 2012].

Lee Kyu-hwa, a senior official of Cheongdo County, said that preliminary quarantine measures had been taken since the case was reported to the local government at 9 a.m.

"The suspected cow shows symptoms of foot-and-mouth disease, such as an excessive drooling of saliva and a refusal to eat," he said, noting that a team of specialists were dispatched to the scene to collect samples from the cow.

Noh Dong-kwang, a senior manager of the Livestock Health Control Association (LHCA), said his agency dispatched 2 officials to the suspected site to prevent the possible spread of the acute, highly contagious viral disease of cloven-hoofed animals.

He said that only one of 8 cows that the farm raises was found to have symptoms. "It is the 1st suspected case of FMD this year [2012]," Noh said.

Another LHCA official said it was possible that the deadly virus could have been taken to the rural area by tourists from China, where thousands of pigs were culled following an outbreak of FMD late last month [November 2012].

"There is also the chance the cow contracted the fatal viral disease from a primitive burial site for pigs and cows after millions of livestock were culled and buried nationwide following the last outbreak of FMD in late November 2010, including in Cheongdo," he said.

"However, it is very unlikely that the same strain of the virus would have affected the cow as all cows here have been vaccinated against it."

The government estimates that the 2010-2011 massive outbreak of the disease led to a financial loss of some 7 trillion won (USD 6.46 billion) to livestock farmers and the culling of 3.4 million cows and pigs.

[Byline: Lee Tae-hoon]

