[Interestingly, 2 months after the seemingly accomplished eradication, in February 2011, of the major, country-wide FMD-O outbreak in South Korea, which had started in 2010, a new case of FMD emerged in a pig farm in North Gyeongsang province -- the same province where the current case is being suspected (see ProMED-mail posting 20110504.1376). North Gyeongsang Province, called in Korean Gyeongsangbuk-do (abbreviated Gyeongbuk), is located in eastern South Korea and can be seen on the map at http://www.nationsonline.org/maps/korea-south-admin-map.jpg.

The 2010/2011 epizootic (155 reported outbreaks) was eventually declared resolved on 22 Apr 2011. Since then, the South Korean Ministry of Agriculture has undertaken extensive efforts in the revision of its surveillance, prevention, and control plans, with considerable investments contemplated.

The recent outbreak in China, referred to in the newswire above, is located in China's north-western province Liaoning, bordering North Korea. Information on the current FMD situation in N. Korea is of interest.

Confirmation (or otherwise) of the described S. Korean case is anticipated. - Mod.AS

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/4pwV.]
